		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Mount Doom 201<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223'>Joseph "Telcontar" Albers</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 13, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">  Okay, sorry this took so long, but I&#39;ve been out of the country, had my cpu crash, and started football since my initial Mount Doom installment. Anyway, here are the cards and their worth IMHO:<br />
<br />
Gondor<br />
<br />
*Aragorn, Elessar Telcontar (5)<br />
Companion Man<br />
Strength 9 Vitality 3 Signet: Frodo<br />
When you play Aragorn, you may heal another companion. At the start of each fellowship phase, you may exert a companion of one culture to heal a companion of another culture.<br />
10 R 25<br />
<br />
Wow, this &#39;Gorn is a tank! At a base of 9 strength, he can take on the biggest, baddest minions right from the get-go. HiDaN has never been stronger, but Elessar Telcontar&#39;s real place is (fittingly) at Arwen&#39;s side in a Last Alliance/The Splendour of Their Banners deck. He can give Greenleaf another shot or let Galadriel &quot;reload&quot; his bow instead. I really like this new &#39;Gorn (plus he shares my name).<br />
<br />
*Cursed of Erech (3)<br />
Companion Wraith<br />
Strength 7 Vitality 3 Signet: None<br />
Enduring. To play, add a threat. When you play Cursed of Erech, exert him twice. At the start of the maneuver phase, you may exert another [Gondor] Wraith to make Cursed of Erech defender +1 until the regroup phase.<br />
10 U 26<br />
<br />
What, no Aragorn signet? No +9 boosts from At His Command? Oh well, Cursed of Erech can hold his own nonetheless. He starts off at 11 strength (and will probably stay there permanently) AND can make your other Wraiths stronger while gaining the defender +1 ability. Just be sure and have a Swept Away out when you play him, or he will become a prime target for Hate and other wounding tech.<br />
<br />
Dead Man of Dunharrow (2)<br />
Companion Wraith<br />
Strength 6 Vitality 3 Signet: None<br />
Enduring. To play, add a threat. When you play this companion, exert him twice.<br />
10 C 27<br />
<br />
Again, no &#39;Gorn signet, but his game-text again makes up for it. The Dead Man is the best non-unique [Gondor] Wraith out there. With Swept Away out, and four of this guy you can get irritated beyond belief as your powerful minions are powerless to stop your opponent. Probably worth packing at least 2 in your [Gondor] Wraith deck.<br />
<br />
*Denethor, Lord of Minas Tirith (2)<br />
Companion Man<br />
Strength 8 Vitality 3 Signet: Aragorn<br />
To play, spot 2 [Gondor] Men. Fellowship: If at a sanctuary, exert Denethor to take a [Gondor] card into hand from your draw deck, then reshuffle. Choose an opponent who may draw 2 cards.<br />
10 R 28<br />
<br />
8 strength for 2 twilight? Game-text aside, LoMT will be seeing play in Knight decks for his cheap fighting power. Add that to his ability to grab forts, swords, companions, artifacts, conditions, events, you name it from your draw deck at sanctuaries and he&#39;s a keeper. Use at Base of Mindolluin to really get set up (you can start him w/Isildur and Ingold). My only problem with him is on deciding whether to use Steward of the City or not, but without a serious drawback, LoMT is the better choice.<br />
<br />
Drawing His Eye (2)<br />
Event Fellowship<br />
For each [Gondor] companion you spot, reveal 1 card at random from a Shadow player&#39;s hand. Choose a revealed Shadow card to be discarded, then its owner draws a card.<br />
10 R 29<br />
<br />
Good in theory, but only really worth using if Sauron, The Witch-King, or Trolls are big in your META. Sure, you might get lucky, but chances are this won&#39;t accomplish anything worth using 2 twilight for.<br />
<br />
End of the Game (0)<br />
Event Skirmish<br />
Make an exhausted [Gondor] companion strength +2. If that companion wins this skirmish, heat that companion or make him or her damage +1.<br />
10 C 30<br />
<br />
A card for the new Wraiths, End of the Game is only really useful in a [Gondor] Wraith deck b/c of the requirement of being exhausted. All in all, End of the Game is a nice card that could give the Wraiths some doubling power if nothing else.<br />
<br />
Every Little is a Gain (1)<br />
Event Maneuver<br />
Spot a [Gondor] Man to discard a stacked Shadow card or to wound a minion bearing a fortification.<br />
10 C 31<br />
<br />
This is almost useless...unless you are playing in a Besieger, Dunland, Goblin Swarms, or Uruk Site Control area that lives off of stacking cards or if you are using First Levels (why?) or the new Fifth Levels, which will probably let you win the skirmish anyway, but I&#39;m getting ahead of myself. Every Little is a Gain is a META choice that is worth using against the afore mentioned Shadows in a Knight or Ranger deck.<br />
<br />
Fifth Level (1)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
Fortification. Bearer is strength -1 for each fortification you can spot. Maneuver: Exert 2 [Gondor] Men or spot 3 knights to transfer this condition to a minion.<br />
10 U 32<br />
<br />
This is the best Fort besides the Fourth Level/Sixth Level combo. Fifth Level makes overwhelming minions for the double. Remember to resolve this skirmish first whenever possible or you may lose other forts and lose track of a minion&#39;s strength. As a last resort, you can always use Turgon to kill off the bearer of this fort before skirmishes. A must have in your knight deck.<br />
<br />
*Hardy Garrison (2)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
To play, spot 2 [Gondor] Men. Each time you lose initiative, you may wound a minion.<br />
10 U 33<br />
<br />
The Gondor doom of initiative condition, Hardy Garrison, when used with Gondorian Swords and Fifth Level can take out those pesky minions w/high vitality. Also worth using in a roaming fortifications deck with Targon, Madril, and Ranger of Osgiliath. For a super cool tech, use this in a Last Alliance deck w/Glimpse of Fate for maximum power!<br />
<br />
Last Throw (5)<br />
Event Regroup<br />
If no opponent controls a site, spot 2 [Gondor] Men to make the move limit +1 for this turn.<br />
10 C 34<br />
<br />
The best triple move card in the game with the exception of Radagast. As long as no opponent controls a site you can triple into 9 for the win. The cost? Five twilight. Even News From the Mark isn&#39;t this easy. Last Throw is a great card to splash in a Knight deck, or even in a Last Alliance deck w/Aragorn and Boromir/Faramir. Consider using Reckless Counter to set this up versus a site control Shadow.<br />
<br />
Rohan<br />
<br />
*Eowyn, Lady of Ithilien (2)<br />
Companion Man<br />
Strength 6 Vitality 3 Signet: Gandalf<br />
Skirmish: Exert Eowyn to choose an opponent. That opponent must wound a minion for each wound on each minion skirmishing Eowyn.<br />
10 R 72<br />
<br />
Nice! The Lady of Ithilien is Rohan&#39;s answer to enduring Nazgul. Too bad there are very few ways to make her defender +1 as she is not valiant. Use Eowyn with the Queen of Elves and Men in a wounding/archery deck to either overwhelm minions or wound them to death. For maximum potential, use Dernhelm&#39;s Blade and give her a Swift Steed or Windfola.<br />
<br />
*Fell Deeds Awake (1)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
To play, spot a [Rohan] Man. Each time you lose initiative, you may liberate a site.<br />
10 U 73<br />
<br />
Rohan&#39;s doom of initiative condition is better than it seems. With Long Spears, Dernhelm&#39;s Blade, Rohirrim Javelins, and many, many boost cards Rohan is one of the easiest cultures to lose initiative. You can even use this during the fellowship phase! Goodbye besiegers and Dunland!<br />
<br />
Unyielding (1)<br />
Event Response<br />
If your [Rohan] Man wins a skirmish, discard a [Rohan] possession to wound a minion or to liberate a site.<br />
10 U 74<br />
<br />
More site liberation, but with the new Eowyn and Fell Deeds Awake, Unyielding should not see much play. If you are running a Swordthain deck, go ahead and splash 1 or 2 in, otherwise there are better cards for you.<br />
<br />
Shire<br />
<br />
Birthday Present (1)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
Fellowship: Add a burden to choose 2 [Shire] events with different card titles from your discard pile. Choose an opponent and make him or her choose 1 of those cards for you to take into hand.<br />
10 R 104<br />
<br />
PATHS or Unheeded? The Shire Countryside decks just got a huge boost with this card. Adding burdens has never been easier! If you play this right, you can give your opponent a headache trying to decide which card to let you have back. Much potential, very good card.<br />
<br />
Brave and Loyal (0)<br />
Event Skirmish<br />
If a Hobbit companion is not assigned to a skirmish, exert that Hobbit to have him or her replace a companion (except the ring-bearer) in a skirmish.<br />
10 U 105<br />
<br />
What!? Sam can&#39;t step in and save Frodo!? Oh well, I guess it would be BA9, but the whole point of the card storywise is ruined. Story aside, Brave and Loyal can effectively make your Hobbit defender +1. Sam can step in and take both The Witch-King and Attea and live to tell about it! Should be included in your super-Hobbit deck.<br />
<br />
Chance Observation (0)<br />
Event Skirmish<br />
If there are 4 or more [Shire] cards in your discard pile, make a Hobbit strength +1 for each Hobbit you can spot.<br />
10 C 106<br />
<br />
This card has much potential in a Shire Countryside/Hobbit Ally deck that uses events. Once you get 4 Shire cards in your discard pile you can gain +8 boosts and turn your Hobbits into mini-wrecking machines.<br />
<br />
Great Heart (1)<br />
Condition<br />
-1 Vitality<br />
Play this condition only during a skirmish. Bearer must be a Hobbit. When this condition is played, wound a minion skirmishing bearer.<br />
10 C 107<br />
<br />
Basically a wound for a wound, use this to save Frodo and then use Seven We Had to discard it and add a burden for Shire Countryside. Great Heart can also be used to trigger A Light in His Mind to remove a burden, but again I am getting ahead of myself, shucks.<br />
<br />
*A Light in His Mind (0)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
Each time you lose initiative, you may spot 2 [Shire] companions to remove a burden.<br />
10 U 108<br />
<br />
The final doom of initiative card definitely one of the best. If you are using Hobbits, you should be losing initiative farely often and removing burdens right and left. Shire Countryside decks have really gained a huge boost in this expansion, by the way.<br />
<br />
Make Haste (0)<br />
Event Maneuver<br />
Stealth. Spot a [Shire] companion and return him or her to your hand to make a Shadow player choose to remove [2] or discard a minion.<br />
10 C 109<br />
<br />
One of the best new Shire cards! Imagine this: You move to site 6 giving off 13 twilight with 5 burdens. Out comes Sauron, Lord of the Rings and he&#39;s licking his chops for two of your little halflings, but you have an ace up your sleeve. You play Make Haste, return Pippin to your hand and prepare to defend yourself against an irate opponent. Definitely worth packing at least 1-2 in any deck that uses Hobbits other than Frodo.<br />
<br />
A Marvel (1)<br />
Event Skirmish<br />
Exert a Hobbit to make another Hobbit strength +3.<br />
10 C 110<br />
<br />
And so the circle is complete. First you could exert a Hobbit to make himself strength +3, then you could exert any non-Hobbit companion to make a Hobbit strength +3 and now you can exert a Hobbit to make another Hobbit strength +3. If you are running many Hobbit allies, A Marvel is the card for you.<br />
<br />
Narrow Escape (0)<br />
Event Regroup<br />
Spot 2 Hobbit companions to make a Shadow player discard a minion (or spot 4 Hobbit companions to make that player discard 2 minions.<br />
10 U 111<br />
<br />
What a boost for Dauntless Hunter! Now you can double without pouring out tons of archery. Use wisely, however, or you may end up discarding a minion that you could live with anyway.<br />
<br />
Nine-Fingered Frodo and the Ring of Doom (0)<br />
Event Skirmish<br />
Tale. Exert a [Shire] character to remove a burden or 2 threats.<br />
10 C 112<br />
<br />
Not bad. For an exertion on any Shire character you can remove either a burden or 2 troublesome threats. Combo this with A Light in His Mind and you can remove burdens two at a time. Shire Countryside again!<br />
<br />
Orc Armor (1)<br />
Possession Armor<br />
Bearer must be a Hobbit. Each Orc and each Uruk-hai skirmishing bearer is strength -1.<br />
10 C 113<br />
<br />
Useful for Frodo in a Dauntless Hunter deck as a last defense against Moria or Stupid Swarm, Orc Armor, like many other new Shire cards, could also be used as part of an all-Hobbit deck that was all but extinct from Fellowship block until now.<br />
<br />
Shadowplay (1)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
To play, spot 2 [Shire] companions. Each time a minion is played, you may exert a Hobbit companion to exert that minion (limit once per turn).<br />
10 U 114<br />
<br />
Essential for every Hobbit deck and useful for DH too, Shadowplay is okay by itself, but with 4 copies out, you can ensure that very few minions slip through unscathed. When used to freshen minions up for Dauntless archery, Shadowplay can be a very pivotal card at least.<br />
<br />
Slunk Out of Sight (1)<br />
Event Skirmish<br />
Stealth. If there are 6 or more [Shire] cards in your discard pile, cancel a skirmish involving your Hobbit and a minion who is not fierce. Each minion in that skirmish is fierce until the regroup phase.<br />
10 U 115<br />
<br />
This card is not as good as it appears. First, requiring 6 or more Shire cards in your discard pile makes this card useless until the late game. Second, most minions who aren&#39;t fierce should not pose much problem for your hobbits anyway, and third, the minion will attack later anyway. I&#39;ll use Brave and Loyal to do basically the same thing any day.<br />
<br />
*The Tale of the Great Ring (0)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
Tale. Skirmish: Prevent a Hobbit from being overwhelmed unless a Shadow event is (or was) played during this skirmish. Discard this condition.<br />
10 U 116<br />
<br />
The next There and Back Again is just as good. While it only effects one Hobbit, it will keep Frodo (or Bilbo) alive regardless of whether they are skirmishing Sauron, or Uruk Rear Guard, unless a Shadow event was played and how often are Shadow events played during skirmishes anyway? I will definitely pack 2-4 of these in my Hobbit deck and this card can find a place in any deck that uses Frodo/Bilbo as its ring-bearer.<br />
<br />
*Frodo, Resolute Hobbit (0)<br />
Companion Hobbit<br />
Strength 3 Vitality 4 Signet: Frodo<br />
Ring-bearer (resistance 12).<br />
10 P 121<br />
<br />
With all of the new corruption strategies introduced in Mount Doom, it&#39;s only fitting that there be a new Frodo who can counter such strategies and Resolute Hobbit does just that. If no other Frodo or other ring-bearer jumps out at you then you could do worse than using the most resistant ring-bearer yet. Will RH replace Courteous Halfling as the &quot;default&quot; Frodo? Only time will tell.<br />
<br />
*Sam, Great Elf Warrior (2)<br />
Companion Hobbit<br />
Strength 3 Vitality 4 Signet: Gandalf<br />
Ring-bound. Sam is strength +1 for each [Shire] companion you can spot. Response: If Frodo dies, make Sam the Ring-bearer (resistance 5).<br />
10 P 122<br />
<br />
Great Elf Warrior is the strongest hobbit companion yet, replacing Merry, From O&#39;er the Brandywine, who needs a Hobbit Sword to attain 7 strength, while Sam needs merely some Hobbit companionship. With several copies of A Promise and the newest Sting, Sam can be as powerful as...well...a Great Elf Warrior!<br />
<br />
 Well, that wraps up this article. Hope you enjoyed the read. Coming up in the near future: Gollum, Isengard, and Raider cultures examined. Until then, signing out...<br />
<br />
Telcontar<br />
&quot;In the high tongue it will not sound so ill&quot;<br />
